#!/bin/sh
# build the xenv.sh static site.
#
# input:  README.md (repo root)
# output: _site/index.html + _site/style.css
#
# dependencies: sh, pandoc, mkdir, cp.
# pandoc 2.0+ (any version on a modern distro will do).

set -eu

ROOT=$(cd "$(dirname "$0")/.." && pwd)
SITE="$ROOT/site"
DIST="$ROOT/_site"

command -v pandoc >/dev/null 2>&1 || {
  echo "site/build: pandoc not found — apt-get install pandoc" >&2
  exit 1
}

mkdir -p "$DIST"

pandoc "$ROOT/README.md" \
  --from=gfm \
  --to=html5 \
  --template="$SITE/template.html" \
  --metadata=title:xenv \
  --no-highlight \
  --output="$DIST/index.html"

cp "$SITE/style.css" "$DIST/style.css"

# tiny robots + a llms.txt so AI crawlers know what this project is.
# (machine-readable summary aimed at coding agents, not just web bots.)
cat > "$DIST/robots.txt" <<'EOF'
User-agent: *
Allow: /
EOF

cat > "$DIST/llms.txt" <<'EOF'
# xenv — the ENV for AI

Encrypted, per-key, commit-safe environment variables. A POSIX shell
script plus openssl. Zero deps, zero lock-in, zero runtime. Every file
in xenv/ is safe to commit; the passphrase is the only secret and it
never lives in the repo.

This file is written for coding agents. If you are an agent in a repo
that contains an `xenv/` directory, this is your operating manual.

## detect

A project uses xenv iff it has an `xenv/` directory:

    xenv/
    ├── README.md                   # project id (YAML frontmatter)
    └── envs/<env>/
        ├── README.md               # KDF params for v3 values (frontmatter)
        └── <KEY>.value.enc         # one encrypted value per file

The environments are the subdirectories of `xenv/envs/` (e.g. production).

## load an env — the thing you almost always want

    xenv @<env> --json   →   {"KEY":"value", ...}   (one JSON object)

Parse with any stdlib JSON parser. It is byte-exact and unambiguous for
values containing '=', quotes, newlines, or whitespace. Do NOT read
`.value.enc` files directly and do NOT reimplement crypto when the `xenv`
binary is present — shell out:

    python3 -c 'import json,subprocess as s; env=json.loads(s.run(["xenv","@production","--json"],capture_output=True,text=True).stdout)'
    node    -e 'const env=JSON.parse(require("child_process").execSync("xenv @production --json"))'
    ruby    -rjson -e 'env=JSON.parse(`xenv @production --json`)'
    sh      -c 'DB=$(xenv @production --json | jq -r .DATABASE_URL)'

`xenv @<env> ./cmd` runs a command with the env injected (nothing hits
disk). `xenv list @<env>` lists key names without the passphrase.

## the passphrase — never commit it

It lives OUTSIDE the repo. For an app or agent at runtime it comes from
an environment variable:

    $XENV_KEY_<ENV>     e.g. $XENV_KEY_PRODUCTION   (env name upper, - → _)
    $XENV_KEY           project-wide fallback

As an agent: read the passphrase from the environment; never seek a key
on disk, never print it, never write it into the repo.

## rules for agents

- NEVER decrypt to a plaintext file you might `git add`. Use `--json`
  (in memory) or `xenv @<env> CMD` (exec-time).
- NEVER write secrets from application code. Writing (set/edit/rotate) is
  a human/CI action; loaders are read-only by design.
- Everything under `xenv/` is safe to commit. The passphrase is the only
  secret, and the design makes it impossible to commit by accident.

## no binary? generate a loader and PROVE it

The wire format is the spec. Each value is one line:

    xenv:v3:<iv>:<ct>:<mac>                       # KDF salt/iter in the env README
    xenv:v4:<salt>:<iter>:<iv>:<ct>:<mac>         # self-contained: salt/iter embedded

Crypto: PBKDF2-SHA256 (200k) → 64 bytes → 32-byte enc-key ‖ 32-byte
mac-key; AES-256-CBC + PKCS#7; HMAC-SHA256, encrypt-then-MAC, scope
"<ver>:…:<iv>:<ct>". A read-only loader is ~20 lines. Full spec:
recipes/README.md.

To prove a generated loader correct with NO tool and NO network, run it
against recipes/vectors/vectors.json — passphrase + envelopes + expected
plaintexts for both wire versions, plus tampered cases that MUST fail.
recipes/vectors/verify.rb and verify.js are reference verifiers.

## finding the binary

    $XENV_BIN   →   ./xenv/bin/xenv (vendored, committed)   →   xenv on $PATH

`xenv setup` vendors a self-contained copy at `xenv/bin/xenv`, so most
checkouts already have it — no install, no download.

## source

https://github.com/ahoward/xenv
EOF

echo "site/build: wrote $DIST/index.html, style.css, robots.txt, llms.txt"
